      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        What to Do When Settlement Is Delayed in Queensland
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Settlement delays happen. Here's what Queensland sellers need to know about their rights, the extension process, penalty interest, and the practical steps to take when a buyer can't settle on time.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>You have exchanged contracts, the cooling-off period has passed, and the settlement date is approaching. Then you receive a call from your solicitor to say the buyer needs more time. For sellers who are simultaneously buying another property, or who have made financial and logistical arrangements based on a specific settlement date, a delay is more than an inconvenience. It can have real financial and practical consequences. Understanding what your rights are and what steps to take immediately will put you in the strongest possible position.</p>

      <p>Settlement delays in Queensland are more common than many sellers expect. The causes are almost always on the buyer's side, but how you respond and how your solicitor manages the process will determine whether the delay costs you money and whether the contract ultimately completes.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why settlements get delayed</h2>
      <p>The most common cause of settlement delays is finance. Even after a buyer has received formal finance approval, delays can occur when the lender's settlement team is overloaded, when the buyer's solicitor has not submitted the correct discharge or settlement instructions in time, or when a last-minute issue emerges during the lender's final title search. In a busy property market or at the end of a financial year, lender settlement teams can be stretched, and even a minor administrative issue can push settlement out by several days.</p>

      <p>Title search issues are another cause. The buyer's solicitor is required to conduct final searches before settlement to confirm there are no outstanding encumbrances, caveats, or notices on the title. If an unexpected issue appears, such as a caveat lodged by a third party or a rates arrears notice that was not cleared, settlement will be delayed until the issue is resolved.</p>

      <p>Solicitor communication breakdowns are more common than they should be. Settlement requires precise coordination between four parties: the seller's solicitor, the buyer's solicitor, the seller's mortgagee (if the property has a mortgage), and the buyer's lender. If any one of those parties has not provided the required documentation, instructions, or funds by the agreed time, settlement cannot proceed. A solicitor who is not proactively managing the process in the week before settlement is a risk factor for delay.</p>

      <p>Buyer-side financial issues beyond their control also occur. A buyer who has sold another property to fund this purchase may be caught in a chain where the settlement on their own sale is delayed. In these situations, the delay is genuine and often outside the buyer's direct control.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The formal extension of settlement process in Queensland</h2>
      <p>Under the standard Queensland REIQ contract, settlement must occur on the date specified. If the buyer cannot settle on that date, they must request a formal extension. Your solicitor will typically receive this request by phone or email, followed by a written extension notice. You are not obligated to agree to an extension, but in practice, refusing to grant one and immediately treating the buyer as in default can have legal consequences that need careful consideration.</p>

      <p>When your solicitor receives an extension request, you have three practical options. You can agree to the extension and document it formally in writing. You can refuse the extension and issue a notice to complete, which formally triggers the buyer's default obligations. Or you can agree to a conditional extension that includes a penalty interest clause for the days of delay. Your solicitor should advise you on which approach best suits your situation, taking into account your own purchase arrangements and the commercial reality of proceeding to default.</p>

      <p>Any extension of settlement must be agreed in writing by both parties and must specify the new settlement date clearly. A verbal agreement to extend is not enforceable under Queensland property law.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Penalty interest and when sellers can claim it</h2>
      <p>The standard REIQ contract provides for penalty interest when a party defaults on settlement. The rate is typically specified in the contract, and it accrues from the date of default (the original settlement date) until actual settlement occurs. For sellers, this means that if you agree to an extension, you are entitled to claim penalty interest on the outstanding balance for each day of delay, unless you have expressly waived that right in the extension agreement.</p>

      <p>In practice, many extension agreements are negotiated without penalty interest, particularly where the delay is short (two to five days) and caused by a lender administrative issue rather than buyer financial failure. Your solicitor should ensure that any decision to waive penalty interest is explicit and documented, rather than implicit in a verbal arrangement.</p>

      <p>For longer delays or where the buyer's financial position is genuinely uncertain, insisting on penalty interest serves two purposes. It compensates you for the direct cost of delay (particularly relevant if you have a loan bridging two properties), and it creates a financial incentive for the buyer to complete settlement as quickly as possible rather than treating the extended date as flexible.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When a delay becomes a default</h2>
      <p>If the buyer fails to settle by the agreed date (including any formally agreed extension), they are in default. To formally trigger default consequences under the REIQ contract, your solicitor must serve a notice to complete. This notice gives the buyer an additional period (typically 14 days, though this can vary) to settle, with a clear statement that failure to do so will constitute a repudiation of the contract.</p>

      <p>If the buyer does not settle within the notice to complete period, you have the right to terminate the contract and retain the deposit. You may also have a claim for additional damages if your actual losses exceed the deposit amount, but this would require separate legal proceedings.</p>

      <p>Terminating a contract and re-listing a property is a serious step with practical consequences. Your property will need to go back to market, potentially at a time when market conditions have changed. The terminated sale may raise questions from future buyers. And if the buyer disputes the termination, you may face a delay or legal challenge before you can proceed. These factors do not mean you should avoid terminating a genuinely defaulting buyer, but they are part of the commercial calculation your solicitor should help you work through.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Practical steps to take immediately</h2>
      <p>When you first hear that settlement may be delayed, contact your solicitor immediately. Do not wait for the formal extension request. Ask them to find out exactly what is causing the delay, who is responsible for resolving it, and what the realistic timeline is. Early and direct communication between solicitors often resolves administrative delays faster than waiting for formal notices to be exchanged.</p>

      <p>If you are also buying another property, contact your own solicitor about the downstream impact. You may need to request an extension from your vendor, and doing so proactively and early is far better than leaving it to the last moment. Most vendors understand that settlement chains create interdependencies, and a professional, early request for an extension will be better received than a panicked last-minute call.</p>

      <p>Contact your bank if you have a mortgage. If the settlement delay affects your own purchase or your ability to discharge your existing mortgage on the expected date, your bank needs to know as early as possible. Lenders are generally cooperative with short delays when given proper notice, but they respond poorly to surprises on the day of settlement.</p>

      <p>Keep a record of every communication about the delay, including the date and time of every phone call and email. If the situation escalates to a formal default and legal proceedings, this documentation will be important.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The emotional and financial reality for simultaneous sellers and buyers</h2>
      <p>For vendors who are simultaneously purchasing another property, a settlement delay is one of the most stressful experiences in the property process. You may have removalists booked, children enrolled in schools, and work arrangements made based on a specific moving date. You may be counting on the settlement proceeds to fund the balance payable on your next home. When that timing collapses, even by a few days, the practical consequences cascade quickly.</p>

      <p>Having a contingency plan is not pessimistic; it is realistic. This means understanding before you go to market how much flexibility you have on your own settlement date, having a short-term accommodation option in mind if needed, and making sure your solicitor is the type who proactively chases progress rather than waiting for issues to land. The best way to avoid being blindsided by a settlement delay is to have a solicitor who is monitoring the process actively in the final two weeks before your settlement date and communicating with all four parties rather than waiting for them to come to them.</p>

